Summary
O
ne and a half years since the International Crimes Division (ICD) in the High Court of Kenya was rst proposed
by the Judicial Service Commission (JSC) in its report of October 2012
1
, there has been little concrete movement
towards actually setting up the Division. This is not in itself a criticism; such processes should take the time necessary
to achieve the desired results. However, apart from publishing the report, making several bench-marking visits to other
countries and holding two low-key workshops, the JSC seems to have made little progress towards actualising an ICD.
Despite this inertia, the Division continues to be touted in ofcial circles as a potential answer to providing justice for
victims of post-election violence as well as a potential replacement of the ICC ongoing process. On at least two occasions,
the Attorney General has gone so far as to erroneously tell international audiences that the ICD has already been
launched.
2
While,ideally, it would make sense to await the production of the nal roadmap towards establishing the ICD,
it is important to offer a preliminary review of the process so far. This will point out potential strengths, weaknesses,
gaps and loopholes, in the hope of ensuring that the eventual outcome of the ICD establishment process is one that will
improve the chances of post-election violence victims nally getting justice.
Background
Following Kenyas disputed presidenal elecons in 2007, violence broke out around the country.
This dark period of the countrys history, now commonly referred to as the post-elecon violence
(PEV), resulted in the death of at least 1,133 Kenyans, the displacement of over 350,000 others,
sexual violence, arson, maiming, loong and the destrucon of property worth millions of shillings.
3
The search for jusce for vicms of post-elecon violence began with the establishment of a
Commission of Inquiry on Post-elecon Violence (CIPEV), mandated to invesgate the facts and
circumstances surrounding the violence and the conduct of state security agencies in handling it
and to make recommendaons on these maers.
CIPEV recommended the creaon of a Special Tribunal for Kenya with Kenyan and internaonal
judges to sit in Kenya to try perpetrators of the violence. It set specic melines during which the
tribunal should be created and operaonalised, failing which it recommended that Ko Annan,
who chaired Kenyas mediaon process, hand over an envelope containing a secret list of alleged
KPTJ
6
perpetrators to the Internaonal Criminal Court (ICC) Prosecutor. Despite three separate aempts,
the government failed to form the tribunal, causing the ICC to intervene.
On 31 March 2010, the ICC Pre-Trial Chamber II authorised the Prosecutor to open invesgaons
into the Kenya situaon.
4
The Prosecutor subsequently issued summons to appear against six
high prole Kenyans and, aer conrmaon hearings held in late 2011, the cases against four
of the suspects, namely Uhuru Kenyaa, William Ruto, Francis Muthaura and Joshua Sang, were
conrmed. The charges against Francis Muthaura were dropped by the Prosecutor, cing the
admission by a crical witness that he had lied in his statement. The trial of Joshua Sang and
William Ruto, the laer now Deputy President of Kenya, opened on 10 September 2013 and is
ongoing, while, aer several adjournments, that of Uhuru Kenyaa, now President of Kenya, is
scheduled to open in October 2014.
Court of last resort
While it is an important feature of the global architecture of the ght against impunity, the
Internaonal Criminal Court is a court of last resort, which exists to complement naonal
criminal jurisdicons under the principle of complementarity.
5
It therefore steps in to prosecute
internaonal crimes only when a member state is unable or unwilling to invesgate and prosecute.
6
Even then, the ICCs prosecutorial policy mandates it to prosecute only those who allegedly bear
the greatest responsibility for the crimes. In Kenyas case, only six individuals appeared before the
Court and the number has since been reduced to three. In a situaon of such widespread violence,
implicang hundreds-and possibly thousands - of mid-level and lower-level perpetrators, domesc
prosecuons are necessary to close the resulng gap in accountability. However, in the case of
Kenya, there have been only a handful of such prosecuons and even fewer convicons.
7
The
recent admission of the Director of Public Prosecuons that the more than 4,000 cases reviewed
by a mul-agency task force set up in June 2012 were not prosecutable, whether as ordinary
crimes or internaonal crimes, seemed all but to exnguish the hope of the post-elecon violence
vicms ever geng jusce in the courts through state-led prosecuons.
8

The Internaonal Crimes Division
of the High Court of Kenya
On 9 May 2012 the Judicial Service Commission (JSC) set up a working commiee mandated to
study and make recommendaons on the viability of establishing an Internaonal Crimes Division
(ICD) in the High Court of Kenya. Aer vising several countries to study various approaches to
domesc prosecuon of internaonal crimes, the commiee produced its rst report in October
2012.
9
The report rightly observes that the Rome Statute obligates member states to punish internaonal
crimes and that the ICC cannot deal with all post-elecon violence cases. It also notes the connuing
demand for jusce following the failure to establish a special tribunal as recommended by the
CIPEV and goes on to recommend the establishment of the ICD.
The legal framework
The legal framework proposed for the formaon of the ICD includes the Constuon, which
establishes the High Court of Kenya with unlimited original jurisdicon on civil and criminal maers;
the Internaonal Crimes Act, No. 16 of 2008 which, under Secon 8 (2), provides that the crimes
proscribed in the Act shall be tried in the High Court of Kenya; and the Judicial Service Act, Secon
5 of which gives the Chief Jusce administrave power to exercise general direcon and control
over the Judiciary and under which, presumably, the Chief Jusce would create the ICD through a
Gazee Noce. The JSC report also provides that the ICD shall apply special rules of procedure,
pracce and evidence in its operaons and conduct of trials.
Jurisdicon
Although the inial discussion of the JSC was on the possibility of operaonalising the Internaonal
Criminal Act, 2008 in order to address pending post-elecon violence cases, the report proposes
that the ICD should now have jurisdicon to prosecute not only crimes under Secon 6 of the
Internaonal Crimes Act - that is, genocide, war crimes and crimes against humanity - but also
transnaonal crimes including drug tracking, human tracking, money laundering, cybercrime,
terrorism and piracy, and any other internaonal crimes as may be proscribed under any
internaonal instrument that Kenya is a party to.
9. Judicial Services Commission, "Report of the Committee of the Judicial Service Commission on the establishment of an
International Crimes Division in the High Court of Kenya" (JSC Report), 30 October 2012.
KPTJ
8
Proposed structure
The report proposes that the ICD should be modelled on the standards of the ICC at The Hague,
with the same rules, pracces and procedures being adopted.
10
Seven judges would be appointed
to sit in the ICD in panels of three, with one extra judge in case one of the judges cannot sit.
Once the judges for this Division have been idened, they would undergo rigorous training in
internaonal criminal law and related subjects, through long-term and short-term courses. The
seat of the proposed Division will be in Nairobi but it can also operate by circuit and may sit and
conduct proceedings in any other place in Kenya as the Chief Jusce may direct.
Prosecuon
The JSC report recommends that there should be established a well-equipped independent
prosecuon unit within the oce of the Director of Public Prosecuons to deal exclusively with
internaonal crimes. At the same me, it also says that Parliament should enact legislaon to
provide for the appointment of a Special Prosecutor who shall be responsible for the prosecuon
of cases that fall within the jurisdicon of the ICD under Arcle 157(12) of the Constuon of
Kenya. These two recommendaons are confusing as they are contradictory. If an independent
prosecuon unit were to be established within the DPPs oce, then it would not be necessary or
feasible to appoint a special prosecutor under Arcle 157(12). The DPP, who has publicly stated
that he regards post-elecon violence cases as unprosecutable, has made clear his reservaons
to what would amount to taking away some of his powers and vesng them in an independent
prosecutor. On the other hand, the appointment of a Special Prosecutor under Arcle 157(12)
would require new legislaon by Parliament and it is highly doubul that the necessary polical
will would be forthcoming.
11
Challenges, Gaps And Weaknesses
Jurisdicon
As already stated, the proposed ICD is to have jurisdicon to prosecute two categories of crime,
namely core internaonal crimes such as genocide, war crimes and crimes against humanity,
and transnaonal and organised crimes, which are domesc crimes with potenal cross-border
elements, such as terrorism, piracy, drug tracking, cybercrime etc. While the JSC report
acknowledges the hitherto limited prosecuons of mid-level and low-level perpetrators of post-
elecon violence as a key driver behind the formaon of the proposed ICD, it does not give a
sound policy juscaon for lumping together both categories of crime. This is intriguing given the
10. It is not clear how the ICD can adopt the rules, practices and procedures of the ICC since the latters rules are an
amalgam of both common law and civil law traditions while Kenya is a purely common law country.
11. See below on anti-accountability environment.
KPTJ
9
fact that the criminal jusce system has had no problems prosecung transnaonal crimes with
some success, even in the absence of a specialised division of the High Court. Further, many of
the transnaonal crimes named are currently prosecutable in the rst instance in the magistrates
courts with possible appeals lying in the High Court, the Court of Appeal and, in appropriate
instances, the Supreme Court. Removing these crimes from the ambit of magistrates courts and
giving the jurisdicon to prosecute them to a division of the High Court would require a change
in legislaon and cannot simply be done by the Chief Jusce through a gazee noce, as the JSC
report seems to envisage.
Giving the proposed ICD the mandate to prosecute both categories of crimes also runs the risk of
the court being kept busy with prosecuons of drug trackers and terror suspects, while never
seriously addressing the more polically sensive cases of post-elecon violence. This would give
the illusion of movement in the search of jusce for post-elecon violence crimes while in reality
the situaon would remain unchanged.
Absence of polical will
The limited number of domesc prosecuons of post-elecon violence crimes is aributable either
to a lack of proper invesgaons or to a lacklustre approach to their prosecuon by the Oce of
the Director of Public Prosecuons, which appears content to tell the public that the cases are
unprosecutable, without stang how the Director of Public Prosecuons has used his considerable
powers under the Constuon to improve their fortunes in court. This lack of polical will, which
has stood in the way of jusce for vicms of post-elecon violence for the last six years, cannot
be xed merely by seng up an internaonal crimes division. This is because, under Kenyas legal
system, judges do not invesgate or prosecute cases; they adjudicate over them as neutral arbiters.
This means that, without meaningful reforms in the invesgave and prosecutorial arms of the
criminal jusce system, the proposed ICD could end up being a white elephant, with no cases to
prosecute.
Hosle, an-accountability environment
Of equal concern is the fact that the debate on the proposed ICD has been taking place in an
ocial environment that is decidedly opposed to accountability. Since the elecon in March 2013
of Uhuru Kenyaa and William Ruto as President and Deputy President respecvely, and despite
surveys consistently showing public support for accountability, the government of Kenya has gone
to great lengths to stop the cases facing the two at the ICC. The fallout from the legal, polical
and diplomac oensive conducted to this end has negavely aected the prospects of obtaining
jusce for vicms of post-elecon violence at home. The most notable example of this is the
KPTJ
10
moon that was passed in the Naonal Assembly and the Senate in September 2013 to withdraw
Kenya from the Rome Statute and to repeal the Internaonal Crimes Act.
12
Although the moon
has not yet been acted upon by the Execuve and Kenya remains a member of the ICC for now, it
is unclear how the ICD would funcon in the absence of the Internaonal Crimes Act, which the
JSC report designates as a key pillar of the ICDs legal framework.
Inadequate witness protecon
The JSC report acknowledges the importance of an eecve witness protecon agency to the
successful prosecuon of internaonal and transnaonal crimes. It recommends that the
government should fully fund and make operaonal the exisng Witness Protecon Agency
(WPA).
13
In so doing, the JSC recognises the inadequacy of the WPA in its current state. This is a
serious shortcoming that has the potenal to sabotage any eorts aimed at domesc accountability
for serious crimes. The WPA is seriously underfunded: in nancial year 2013/2014, it received
only Ksh 196 million (2.2 million US dollars) of the Ksh 500 million (six million US dollars) that it
requested.
According to experts, witness protecon in Kenya seems to lack the polical support necessary
to make it eecve because it is viewed in the light of the ICC and the eorts to hold high prole
policians accountable.
14
The WPA also has an image problem that makes it dicult for potenal
witnesses to entrust it with their safety, especially when they are called upon to tesfy against
powerful polical interests. While it is formally independent, the fact that the WPA began its life as
a department in the Oce of the Aorney General and that its board includes senior government
ocials, among them the Aorney General, the Inspector General of Police and the Head of the
Naonal Intelligence Service, may make potenal witnesses doubt its independence from the
execuve arm of the government.
Retroacve prosecuon of internaonal crimes
The JSC report recognises a potenal obstacle to prosecung post-elecon violence crimes as
internaonal crimes under the Internaonal Crimes Act. This is because the Act came into force in
January 2009, prior to which core internaonal crimes of genocide, war crimes and crimes against
humanity did not exist as such in the laws of Kenya. It is a general principle of both internaonal law
and the Kenyan Constuon that a person cannot be punished for an act that did not constute
12. Kenya parliament votes to withdraw from ICC, Al Jazeera Africa, http://www.aljazeera.com/news/
africa/2013/09/201395151027359326.html
13. JSC Report, page 149
14. Wanja Gathu, Institute of War and Peace Reporting, Big Questions About Witness Protection in Kenya. 27 May 2014 - http://
iwpr.net/report-news/big-questions-about-witness-protection-kenya
KPTJ
11
an oence at the me it was commied. This is known as the principle of non-retroacvity of
the law. This refers to the requirement that the law should not extend its scope to maers that
occurred before the law was enacted. This legal principle is best encapsulated in the Lan maxim
as nullum crimen, nulla poena sine lege scripta, meaning nothing is a crime and no punishment
may be imposed except by a wrien law or nullum crimen, nulla poena sine lege praevia, which
translates as nothing is a crime except as provided by law and no punishment may be imposed
except as previuosly provided by law; that is to say, the law must pre-exist the crime.
Kenya raed the Rome Statute in 2005 and domescated it through the Internaonal Crimes Act
in 2008, aer the post-elecon violence. The Act became operaonal on 1 January 2009. The Act
provides for prosecuon of crimes against humanity domescally in Kenya but cannot be applied
to crimes that were perpetrated between 2007-2008 before the Act was passed into law.
In its report, the JSC has argued that there should be no reason under internaonal law that the
Internaonal Crimes Act, or any other subsequent Act, cannot be used to prosecute crimes that
predate its enactment. This is because the principle of non-retroacvity would not be violated
where the conduct to be prosecuted was already a crime under internaonal law.
Unsound legal interpretaon?
The report suggests that since the Constuon of Kenya 2010 acknowledges that all convenons
raed by the State are part of Kenyan law, then the Rome Statute was a part of Kenyan law from
2005, when Kenya raed it. As such, the report argues, perpetrators of internaonal crimes in
2007-2008 were therefore comming pre-exisng crimes and can be prosecuted under the Rome
Statute as read with the Penal Code and should not be limited by the Internaonal Crimes Act.
However, not only is this an expedient interpretaon of the law, it is not legally sound. This is
because treaes are specic as to me, content and jurisdicon. They come into force only upon
racaon and, where a State's legal system is dualist, a further step of domescaon is required.
A dualist state, as opposed to a monist one, is a state whose laws require that all treaes, in addion
to being signed and raed by the state, must be adopted through naonal legislaon before their
provisions can become part of the domesc law. At the me of racaon of the Rome Statute,
Kenya was a dualist state and therefore domescaon was necessary. Kenya domescated the
Rome Statute in 2008 aer the post-elecon violence and therefore the treaty only has eect
aer this domescaon. It would be important to clearly establish why this case should be an
excepon, which the JSC report does not do convincingly.
Secondly, an observaon of analogous situaons indicates that retroacvity cannot be provided
for in a carte blanche provision that allows a look into all past atrocies of a naon. Whilst following
KPTJ
12
the JSCs recommendaon would mean the possible prosecuon of all alleged internaonal crimes
commied aer 2005, best pracce in Timor lEste, Rwanda and the Democrac Republic of Congo
shows that a retroacve clause in legislaon should be limited to a specic me to deal with a
specic atrocity and not be open to all past historical injusces. There has to be a limited scope
in which the retroacvity provision operates, in order to prevent states from assuming unlimited
power and potenally abusing this provision. Therefore, while it is important and necessary to
prosecute serious post-elecon crimes as internaonal crimes, more thought needs to be given to
how to get around the retroacvity obstacle than the JSC has included in its report. This will avoid
the danger of the prosecuons being challenged for unconstuonality once they get underway.
Lack of stakeholder input
The process of debang the possible establishment of the ICD has been faulted for lacking adequate
consultaon with key stakeholders, especially relevant civil society actors and vicm groups. Long
before the JSC recommended the formaon of the ICD, civil society had been grappling with the
challenge of closing the gap in prosecuons and had held various consultaons and produced
a number of reports on the issue.
15
However, when the JSC process got under way, there was
no aempt to bring civil society on board at the outset. What passed for consultaon was a
breakfast meeng at which the JSC shared its proposals with lile room for feedback. Subsequent
communicaons between the JSC and civil society on the issue have been intermient and
procedural, without a plaorm for proper engagement in which the JSC might respond to civil
societys concerns and incorporate its input into the process.
Posive complementarity
The purpose of establishing a domesc mechanism to prosecute crimes against humanity through
an ICD or other mechanism is to complement exisng prosecuon at the Internaonal Criminal
Court (ICC) and not to replace the ICC process, as some local proponents of the ICD have suggested.
The prosecuons at the ICD also have to be a legimate eort to pursue jusce for vicms of
post-elecon violence in accordance with internaonal standards and not designed to shield
perpetrators of crimes against humanity from jusce.
In addion, ICD proceedings should be designed to plug the gap in the prosecuon of mid to lower
level perpetrators, and not merely to iniate token prosecuon of lower-level perpetrators so as
to disguise the lack of prosecuon of elite perpetrators. This means that the ICD must also pursue
higher-level suspects. Only then can the ICD be viewed to be legimate. Legimacy would also be
15. e.g. Kenyans for Peace with Truth and Justice, The Post-Election Violence in Kenya: Seeking Justice for Victims. http://www.
africog.org/reports/KPTJ%20SPECIAL%20REPORT_Seeking%20Justice%20for%20PEV%20Victims.pdf
KPTJ
13
conferred on the ICD if it had judges and prosecutors drawn from among local and internaonal
legal praconers, judges and scholars. This would give it access to internaonal best pracce and
experse, as well as address any suspicion of potenal bias that tends to accompany domesc
instuons that seek to pursue jusce in a polically polarised environment such as that in Kenya.
Recommendaons
The JSC sub-commiee on the establishment of the ICD should embark on proper consultaons
with key actors including relevant civil society organisaons, vicm groups and academics, to
develop proper consensus on how to establish an adequate complementarity mechanism for
Kenya.
The JSC reports proposal to retroacvely prosecute post-elecon crimes as internaonal crimes
needs to be beer thought out and supported, if the Internaonal Crimes Act is to remain the
legal basis to prosecute crimes from 2007/8. Part of the JSCs arguments must emphasise the
grave nature of internaonal crimes and that the obligaon to prosecute is incumbent on all
states under internaonal law. An acknowledgement by the Internaonal Law Commission and
the Internaonal Court of Jusce that crimes against humanity are violaons of jus cogens (that
is, certain fundamental, overriding principles of internaonal law, from which no derogaon is
ever permied) means that the responsibility to prosecute these violaons cannot be limited by
naonal statute even as concerns retroacvity.
Despite the diculty in obtaining the necessary polical will, the legislave framework
establishing the ICD should be a parliamentary statute as opposed to an administrave decision
by the Chief Jusce, as appears to be currently envisaged. This will insulate the process of
invesgaon and prosecuon from subsequent polical interference whilst providing a legal
basis both for funding as well as administrave funcons such as issuance of summons. A statute
would also provide a legal framework for engagement with experts in internaonal criminal
jusce, allowing for the possible secondment of internaonal actors, such as prosecutors and
possibly judicial ocers. The statute would also regulate the qualicaons of persons to be
appointed as prosecutors.
There is a need to harmonise all relevant legislaon, parcularly the Evidence Act, to respond to
evidenary standards for crimes commied in an environment of conict or generalised violence;
the Criminal Procedure Code, in light of the unique requirements of prosecung internaonal
crimes and the Penal Code to provide a basis for sentencing alongside the Internaonal Crimes
Act, should it be amended to apply retroacvely.
KPTJ
14
With regard to the jurisdicon of the ICD, whereas the inclusion of transnaonal and organised
crimes widens the ambit of the ICD by giving it a role beyond internaonal crimes, the High
Court of Kenya as presently constuted, as well as the Penal Code, Criminal Procedure Code,
internaonal convenons raed by Kenya which form part of Kenyan law through Arcle 2 (5)
and 2 (6) of the Constuon of Kenya and relevant statutes, are able to address these violaons
and have already done so in the past fairly successfully.
16
It is therefore necessary for the JSC to
clearly jusfy the proposed mixed jurisdicon of the ICD. A beer alternave, given the urgency
of addressing post-elecon violence, would be to sequence the work of the ICD so that it deals
with post-elecon violence cases on a priority basis, aer which its jurisdicon may be expanded
to include transnaonal crimes.
Conclusion
The recommendaon to establish an Internaonal Crimes Division of the High Court of Kenya
is welcome in principle, as part of the enduring search for jusce for vicms of post-elecon
violence. However the Judicial Service Commission report recommending the establishment of
the ICD raises as many quesons as it aempts to answer. Much more thought needs to be put
into addressing concerns regarding the proposed legal framework, the mixed jurisdicon of the
ICD, the invesgaon and prosecuon of the crimes, witness protecon and the harmonisaon of
exisng legislaon necessary to ensure that the resulng mechanism becomes a real opon for
delivering jusce for vicms of post-elecon violence. Key actors and stakeholders in the search for
jusce, especially vicm groups and relevant civil society organisaons that have worked on and
thought about these issues consistently, and for a sustained period of me, should be genuinely
engaged and their input sought for every stage of the process. These measures are necessary to
ensure that once established, the proposed Internaonal Crimes Division becomes a viable opon
for jusce for vicms of post-elecon violence and not just an expensive white elephant.
